This week we look at gambling tax rates across Europe, in the context of a possible UK rise in the Autumn Budget. Our weekly also includes a summary of our latest research, and global valuation comps.
Exhibit 1: Chart of the week: Gambling tax rates
Source: Vixio and National Regulator Data. Shown as rates on GGR, with gross win margin assumptions made for turnover tax based regimes.

Our chart shows online gambling tax rates across European jurisdictions. The potential for tax rises in the UK's forthcoming Autumn Budget has been firmly an investor debate in recent weeks. The chart shows that UK rates are low compared to European averages; we see this and clear fiscal need as the drivers behind a potential hike. We see two strands: 1/ tax harmonisation and 2/ a discrete raise of rates. Interestingly, the chart shows that most European jurisdictions have the same tax rates for sports betting and online casino (Italy materially the same), noting that online casino is not locally regulated in Ireland, France and Poland (Germany slots rates are married with sports betting, with casino not widely regulated at state level). Given this context and the ongoing multi- year process to harmonise rates, we see a wide differential in UK rates as unlikely. Separately, we note negative externalities (UK- based technology jobs, impact on e.g. horse racing, reduced channelisation) as factors against a (material) tax rise. We discussed these factors more fully, as well as sensitivities for our coverage in this note: UK Tax Risk Debate & Sensitivities.
